      "description": "The algorithm iterates over every active large‑period train on each day. For trains with period p > B (B = 300) the code stores them in `large_active` and, after processing the day's operation, loops over `large_active.items()` to check whether each train is in maintenance. In the worst case there can be O(n) active large‑period trains for O(m) days, giving O(m·n) time (up to ~4·10^10 operations for n = m = 2·10^5). This exceeds the time limit.",
      "triggering_input": "200000 200000\n1 301\n1 301\n... (repeat the line \"1 301\" 200000 times for the n model definitions) ...\n1 1\n1 2\n1 3\n... (add each of the 200000 models on a distinct day) ...\n",
      "fix": "Replace the per‑day iteration over `large_active` with a more efficient method. One common approach is to treat large periods by scheduling their maintenance intervals in a difference array or using a Fenwick/segment tree. For each added large‑period train, pre‑compute the days on which it will be in maintenance (they appear every p days for a contiguous block of length y) and add +1 at the start and -1 after the block for each occurrence, using a loop that steps by p (which is at most 2·10^5 / B ≈ 667 iterations per train). This yields total O((n+m)·√maxPeriod) time, which fits the limits. Alternatively, keep a separate array for each large period and update it lazily, or use the “small‑large” decomposition where the number of large‑period trains processed per day is bounded by O(√maxPeriod).",
      "confirmed": true,
      "reasoning": "The current implementation works correctly for small periods but fails to scale when many trains have periods larger than the threshold B. The inner loop over `large_active` is executed for every day, leading to quadratic time in the worst case, which will cause a Time Limit Exceeded (TLE) on the maximal test data. The suggested fix eliminates the per‑day linear scan of all large‑period trains, bringing the complexity down to acceptable levels."
    }
  ]
